      "task": "Users report that replacing an id's complete tag set can leave removed tags visible through reverse lookup. Before editing, run the included node repro/bidirectional-tag-index.mjs and use its structured output to identify the first incorrect transition. Fix createTagIndex() with the exact method surface { set, remove, getTags, getIds }. Every id and tag must be a nonempty primitive string. set(id, tags) must validate tags as a dense array with no extra own keys, only own enumerable data elements, and unique tag strings before changing state; it atomically replaces the id's entire current tag set, updates both forward and reverse links, preserves existing current associations' insertion positions, appends newly created associations in input order, returns true exactly when the stored association set changes or the id is first created, and returns false for the same set regardless of supplied order. remove(id) must clear both directions and return whether the id existed, including an id stored with no tags. getTags(id) and getIds(tag) must return fresh arrays in first-current-association insertion order, so removing and later re-adding an association moves it to the end; caller mutations must not affect state. Preserve all inputs, reject invalid input with TypeError without invoking array accessors, preserve the exact direct and public named export surfaces, and keep createTagIndex as the only direct named export. Add focused regressions for replacement cleanup, new reverse links, removal, stable and re-add ordering, atomic validation, fresh getter arrays, empty sets, and API compatibility. Run the full test suite and rerun the same included repro, whose first nonblank JSON object must match the resolved behavior. Do not commit, install packages, use the network, or create another worktree.",
